'''Davyum''' was the proposed name for a [[chemical element]] found by [[chemist]] [[Serge Kern]] in 1877.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/14786447708639315 | title = On a new metal, davyum| first = Serge | last = Kern | journal = Philosophical Magazine |series=Series 5 | volume =   4 | year =  1877 | pages = 158&ndash;159 | issue = 23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/14786447708639360 | title = On a new metal, davyum| first = Serge | last = Kern | journal = Philosophical Magazine |series=Series 5 | volume =   4 | year =  1877 | pages = 395&ndash;396 | issue = 26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = https://archive.org/stream/nature15unkngoog/nature15unkngoog_djvu.txt | doi = 10.1038/017245a0 | title = Davyum1 | year = 1878 | journal = Nature | volume = 17 | pages = 245 | issue=430|bibcode = 1878Natur..17..245. }}</ref> It was shown that the material was a [[mixture (chemistry)|mixture]] of [[iridium]] and [[rhodium]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi =10.1002/ange.19270400905 | title =Dwimangan in Platinerzen | year =1927 | last1 =Swjaginzew | first1 =O. | last2 =Korsunski | last3 =Seljakow| first2 =M. | first3 =N. | journal =Zeitschrift für Angewandte Chemie | volume =40 | pages =256 | issue =9 }}</ref> In 1950 it was proposed that the new [[metal]] might also have contained [[rhenium]], which had not been discovered in Kern's time.<ref>{{cite journal | doi =  10.1038/165819a0 | title =  Davyum, a Possible Precursor of Rhenium (Element 75) | year =  1950 | last1 =  Friend | first1 =  J. Newton | last2 =  Druce  | first2 =  J. G. F. | journal =  Nature | volume =  165 | pages =  819 | issue=4203|bibcode = 1950Natur.165..819F }}</ref>

