{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}
'''Radical sustainability''' recognizes that a system is not [[sustainable]] if any part of it is unsustainable. An [[economy]] cannot be sustained if the underlying [[social structure]] is unsustainable. A social structure cannot be sustained if the [[environment (biophysical)|environment]] it depends upon is unsustainable. Vice versa we find that in our modern day the environment cannot be sustained unless proper economical and social practices are in place.
{{Quote|text=A radical sustainability viewpoint recognizes the inseparability of [[environmental issues|ecological]] and [[social issues]] and the necessity of ensuring the solution to one problem does not create or worsen another.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kellogg, S.|author2=Pettigrew, S.|year=2008|title=Toolbox for sustainable city living|publisher=South end press, Massachusetts|isbn=978-0896087804}}</ref>}}
The [[wikt:Special:Search/radical|radical]] sustainable philosophy addressed problems of sustainability through a [[Top-down and bottom-up design|bottom-up approach]] - a form of "grass roots" sustainability.
Radical sustainability advocates and supports [[autonomy|autonomous]] development, [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous]] movements, [[women's rights]], [[social justice]] and [[Green politics|green]] practices.
== Examples == There are widespread examples of radical sustainability including [[open source ecology]], [[rainwater harvesting]] (e.g. the projects by [[Brad Lancaster]]) and the [[Bushmen]] who live a life where social and environmental aspects are completely intertwined.
==See also== *[[Interdependence]] *[[Green economy]] *[[Ecological economics]] *[[Eco-socialism]]
